He told me he would accept all the help he could get.
And I was there to help.
When I left Tony, I felt the burning and salt of the tears that came to my eyes.
I felt the weight of the revelation that I could sit in a room, one evening, where a few hundred people had 500 billion dollars and in another room, two days later, just 5 kilometers away, where a man lived without pay for a child to have his only meal of the day.
It wasn't the glaring inequality that made me want to cry. It was not the thought of these hungry children, homeless, it was not rabies towards the 1% or pity towards the 99%.
No, I was disturbed because I finally realized that I was the dialysis of a country that needed a kidney transplant.
I realized that my story replaced all those who were expected to take charge of them, even if they had nothing to grip to take charge of themselves; that my body replaced all the structural, systemic aid that never went to Harlem, or the Appalachians or the floor -9, that my voice replaced all those voices that seemed too ignorant, too proletarian.
And that shame, that shame has overwhelmed me, like the shame of sitting in front of the TV watching Peter Jennings announce the new millennium, again, and again, and again.
I had been deceived, deceived, boosed.
But this time, the fake Savior was me.
You see, I've come a long way from the altar, the night I thought the world was coming to an end, from a world where people spoke in tongues, considered suffering a necessary act of God, and took a text as an infallible truth.
Yes, I've come so far that I find myself exactly where I started.
Because it’s simply wrong to say that we live in an era of unbelief — no, we believe today as much as before.
Some of us may believe in the prophecy of Brené Brown or Tony Robbins.
We can believe in the New Yorker Bible or the Harvard Business Review.
We can believe deeply when we worship here, at TED Church, but we desperately want to believe, we need to believe.
We speak the language of charismatic leaders who promise to solve all our problems.
We see suffering as a necessary act of capitalism, our God. We take the text of technological progress as the infallible truth.
And we barely realize the human price we pay, when we fail to question a brick, lest it destroy all our foundations.
But if you are disturbed by the unacceptable things we have finally accepted, then it must be time for a questioning.
I have no disruption or innovation gospel, or a triple line of results.
Actually, I don't have a gospel of faith to share with you today.
I have, and I offer, a gospel of doubt.
The gospel of doubt does not require that you cease to believe, but that you believe in something new: that it is possible not to believe.
It is possible that the answers are false, that the questions themselves are false.
Yes, the gospel of doubt means that it is possible that we, on this stage, in this room, are wrong.
Because it raises the question: “Why? »
With all the power we hold in our hands, why are people still suffering so much?
This doubt leads me to share that we place my organization, MBAs Across America, in cessation of activity.
We have fired our team and closed our doors, and we will share our model freely with all those who seize the power to do this work without waiting for our permission.
This doubt forces me to give up the role of savior that some expect of me, because there is not enough time and our chances are too slim to wait for the seconds to come, when the truth is that there will be no miracles here.
And this doubt, it regenerates me, it gives me hope, that when our problems overwhelm us, when the paths designed for us seem to lead us to our loss, when our healers bring no help to our wounds, it will not be our blind faith — no, it will be our humble doubt that will illuminate a little the darkness of our lives and our world, and will allow us to make our voices heard to whisper
or to shout, or simply say, very simply: “There must be another way. »
