Sometimes I feel ashamed to be a European.
Last year, more than a million people in need of our help arrived in Europe and our response was frankly pathetic.
There are so many contradictions.
We mourn the tragic death of Alan Kurdi, a two-year-old child, and yet, since then, more than 200 children have drowned in the Mediterranean.
International treaties recognize that refugees are a collective responsibility, and yet we accept that the small Lebanon welcomes more Syrians than the whole of Europe combined.
We lament the existence of smugglers, yet we are making it the only viable route to seek asylum in Europe.
We lack the workforce, yet we prevent people who meet our economic and demographic needs to come to Europe.
We proclaim our liberal values in opposition to fundamentalist Islam, however -- we have policies of repression that arrest minor asylum seekers, separate children from their families and seize the property of refugees.
What are we doing?
How did we get to this point that we adopted such an inhumane response to a humanitarian crisis?
I don't think it's because of a disinterest, at least I don't want to believe it.
I believe that it is because our politicians have no vision, that they do not know how to adapt the international rules of asylum, created more than 50 years ago, to globalization.
I want to take a step back and ask two fundamental questions, the two questions that we all have to ask.
First, why is the current system not working?
Second, how can we fix it?
The current refugee regime was created as a result of the consequences of the Second World War by these people.
Its primary purpose is to ensure that when a state fails, or worse, turns against its people, people have a place to go, where to live in safety and with dignity until they can return.
It was created precisely for situations such as the current situation in Syria.
Through an international convention signed by 147 governments, the 1951 Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, and an international organization, UNHCR, States have pledged to admit to each other people fleeing conflict and persecution on their territory.
But today, this system fails.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In practice, our immigration policies are blocking the path to security.
In theory, refugees have the right to integration or return to their country of origin.
But in practice, they get stuck in eternal limbo.
In theory, refugees are a common global responsibility.
In practice, geography means that countries close to the conflict welcome the overwhelming majority of refugees.
The system is not broken because the rules are bad
but because we do not properly apply them to a changing world, and that is what we must reconsider.
I will explain how the current system works.
How does the current refugee regime work?
But not from an institutional perspective, rather from the perspective of a refugee.
Imagine a Syrian woman. Let's call her Amira.
For me, Amira represents
Many people I have met in the area.
Amira, like 25% of the world’s refugees, is a woman with children, and she can’t go home because she’s from this city you see: Homs. A city that was beautiful and historic and is now in ruins.
Amira can't go back.
But Amira has no hope of settling in a third country, because there is a lottery available at only less than 1% of refugees.
Amira and her family face an impossible choice.
They have three options.
The first option is that Amira takes her family to a camp.
In the camp, she could be helped, but there is little future for Amira and her family.
The camps are in austere and arid places, often in the desert.
In the Zaatari camp in Jordan, at night, you hear the bombings across the border.
Economic activity is restricted.
Education is often of poor quality.
Around 80% of the refugees in camps worldwide must stay there for at least 5 years.
It’s a miserable life, and that’s probably why, in reality, only 9% of Syrians choose this option.
An alternative for Amira is to head to the urban area of a neighboring country, such as Amman or Beirut.
It is an option chosen by about 75% of Syrian refugees.
But it also has difficulties.
Refugees in such urban areas often do not have the right to work.
They often do not have access to help.
And so when Amira and her family have spent all their savings, they will have nothing and will be in urban misery.
There is a third possibility that an increasing number of Syrians will choose.
Amira can seek hope for her family by risking their lives on a dangerous and perilous journey to another country, and that is what we are seeing today in Europe.
We therefore offer refugees an almost impossible choice between three options: camp, urban misery or a dangerous journey.
For refugees, this choice is today's refugee system.
But I think that's a fake choice.
We can reconsider this choice.
The reason we limit these options is because we think these are the only options for refugees, but they are not.
Politicians see this as a zero-sum problem, if we benefit refugees, citizens pay the price.
We tend to think that refugees are an inevitable cost or a burden to society.
But they don't have to be. They can contribute.
What I mean is that there are ways to increase opportunities and that everyone benefits from it: host countries and communities, our societies and refugees.
And I want to suggest four ways to transform our vision of refugees.
These four points of view have one thing in common: they include opportunities for globalization, mobility and markets, and modernize the way we think about the refugee problem.
The first idea is that of favorable environments. It begins with the fundamental recognition that refugees are human beings like everyone else, but with extraordinary circumstances.
Together with my colleagues in Oxford, we embarked on a research project in Uganda, observing the economic life of the refugees.
We chose Uganda, not because it is representative of all host countries.
He's exceptional.
Unlike the majority of host countries, Uganda has given refugees an economic opportunity.
It gives them the right to work, the freedom to move.
And the results are extraordinary, for the refugees and for the host community.
In the capital, Kampala, we discovered that 21% of refugees own a trade employing people and 40% of these employees are natives of the host country.
In other words, refugees create work for the citizens of the host country.
Even in the camps, we have discovered extraordinary examples of dynamic and flourishing businesses.
For example, in a village called Nakivale, we have the example of Congolese refugees running digital music sharing companies.
We found a Rwandan who runs a company to allow young people to play video games on consoles and recycled televisions.
Despite the difficulties of extreme constraints, the refugees innovate and the man you see is a Congolese named Demou-Kay.
Demou-Kay arrived in the camp with very few possessions, but he wanted to become a director.
So, with friends and colleagues, he started a community radio station, he rented a camera and made movies.
He has made two documentaries with and for our team and he is creating a successful business with almost nothing.
These are the examples that should guide our response to refugees.
Rather than seeing refugees as inevitably dependent on humanitarian aid, we must provide them with the opportunity for human development.
Yes, clothes, blankets, shelter, food are very important in the emergency phase, but we have to go further.
We must offer the opportunity for connectivity, electricity, education, the right to work, access to banks.
Anything we take for granted, which integrates us into the global economy can and should be offered to refugees.
The second idea I want to talk about is the economic zones.
Unfortunately, not all host countries in the world have the approach that Uganda has.
Most host countries do not open their economies to refugees in this way.
But there are always pragmatic options that we can use.
Last April, I went to Jordan with my colleague, the development economist, Paul Collier, and we thought about an idea we had there with the international community and the government, an idea to create jobs for Syrians while supporting Jordan’s national development strategy.
This is the idea of an economic zone where we could potentially integrate the employment of refugees and the employment of the natives of the host country.
15 minutes from the Zaatari camp, which hosts 83 000 refugees, there is the development zone of King Hussein Bin Talal.
The government spent more than 100 million dollars connecting it to the power grid and the road network, but there were two things missing: access to labour and foreign investment
so that refugees can work there rather than being stranded in camps, support their families, develop skills through vocational training before returning to Syria.
We recognized that Jordan would benefit from it, its development strategy requiring the transition from a middle-income country to an industrial country.
Refugees would benefit, but it would also contribute to the reconstruction of Syria after the war, acknowledging that we must incubate refugees because they are the best resource to rebuild Syria.
We published this idea in the journal Foreign Affairs.
King Abdullah has taken up the idea.
This was announced at the London Conference on Syria and a test will begin during the summer.
The third idea I want to submit to you is the notion of preference between states and refugees leading to positive results that you see in this selfie where Angela Merkel and a Syrian refugee are featured.
We rarely ask refugees what they want, where they want to go, but we can do it and it will be better for everyone.
The economist Alvin Roth developed the idea of market adequacy, where the order of preference of the parties determines their possible correspondence.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Teytelboym looked for ways to apply this idea to refugees, to ask refugees to rank destinations but also to allow states to classify the type of refugees desired on skills or language criteria, and then match them.
Of course, quotas on diversity and vulnerability should be put in place, but this is one way to increase the chances of correspondence.
The idea of correspondence is successfully used to, for example, distribute students to the university, match kidney donors and patients, and the algorithm exists on dating sites.
Why not apply this to give refugees choice?
It could also be used at the national level where one of the biggest challenges is to persuade local communities to accept refugees.
Currently, in my country, for example, we often send engineers to rural areas and farmers to the city, which makes no sense.
Markets in adequacy make it possible to gather these preferences and to listen to the needs and demands of the host population and refugees.
The fourth idea I want to talk about is the principle of humanitarian visa.
The tragedies and disorders observed in Europe could have been avoided.
They come from a fundamental contradiction in the European policy on asylum: in order to seek asylum in Europe, you must arrive spontaneously by embarking on a dangerous journey that I have already spoken of.
But why are these journeys necessary in the era of low-cost airlines and modern consular means?
These trips are not necessary and, last year, they led to the death of more than 3 000 people on the borders of Europe and on European territory.
If refugees had the right to travel directly and to seek asylum in Europe, we would avoid that. And we can do this through humanitarian visas that allow people to obtain a visa from an embassy or consulate of a neighboring country and then pay for their journey by ferry or plane to Europe.
It costs about €1 000 to pay a smuggler from Turkey to the Greek islands.
A low-cost flight from Bodrum to Frankfurt is €200.
If we allowed refugees, it would have major benefits.
This would save lives, it would diminish the smugglers’ market and mark the end of the disorder observed on the European front line in areas like the Greek islands.
It is the laws that prevent us from doing so, not a rational solution.
This is an idea that has been applied.
Brazil has taken a forward-thinking approach and more than 2 000 Syrians have obtained humanitarian visas, went to Brazil and, upon arrival, have applied for refugee status.
In this configuration, every Syrian who did this received refugee status and was recognized as a refugee.
There is a historical precedent.
Between 1922 and 1942, these Nansen passports were used as travel documents authorizing 450 000 Assyrians, Turks and Chechens to travel to Europe and apply for refugee status elsewhere in Europe.
And the Nansen International Refugee Office has received the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of this viable strategy.
Each of these four ideas that I have presented to you are ways to expand Amira's choices.
These are ways that we have to increase the choice of refugees beyond these options, these three impossible options that I have detailed, while benefiting others.
In conclusion, we need a new perspective a vision that extends the choice of refugees but recognizes that they do not have to be a burden.
There is nothing inevitable about the fact that refugees are a cost.
Yes, they are a humanitarian responsibility, but they are human beings with skills, talents, aspirations and the ability to contribute, if we allow them.
In the new world, migration will not stop.
What we have seen in Europe will continue for years.
People will still travel, people will be displaced and we need to find rational and realistic ways to manage it, not based on the old logics of humanitarian aid, charity, but built on the opportunities offered by globalization, markets and mobility.
I urge you to wake up and urge our politicians to wake up to this challenge.
Thank you very much.
When I was little, I dreamed of the ocean.
A wild place, very colorful and full of life, harboring strange and fantastic creatures.
I imagined big sharks reigning supreme and graceful sea turtles twirling through the corals.
First a marine biologist, then a photographer, I spent most of my career looking for places as magical as those I dreamed of.
As you can see, I started exploring the water very early on.
But the first time I really went underwater, I was about 10 years old.
I remember perfectly giving determined palms to reach this old cannon embedded in a shallow coral reef.
When I was finally able to catch it, I looked up and found myself surrounded by fish of all the colors of the rainbow.
That day, I fell in love with the ocean.
Thomas Peschak Photographer specializing in marine conservation In 40 years on Earth, I had the immense privilege of exploring some of the wildest seascapes for National Geographic and the Save Our Seas Foundation.
I photographed everything, from huge sharks to the tiny ones holding in the palm of my hand.
I felt the fish in the breath of the humpback whales feeding next to me in the cold waters of Canada, near the Great Bear Rainforest.
I even knew everything about the rituals in love with the green turtle in the Mozambique Channel.
We all leave a footprint on the ocean and vice versa.
And the pristine seas I dreamed of are always harder to find.
They are always smaller and more threatened.
While we humans maintain our role as the largest predator on the planet, I have witnessed direct repercussions and photographed them.
I thought for a long time I had to shock my audience with images that disturb to get him out of his indifference.
This approach has its merits, but I came back.
In my opinion, the best way to make a change is to sell love.
If you want, I'm a couple-maker and, as a photographer, I have an exceptional opportunity to reveal entire animals and ecosystems beneath the ocean surface.
You can’t love and fight for something if you don’t know about its existence.
Revealing this - that's all the power of marine photography.
Among the hundreds of underwater places I have seen, a handful of these landscapes have deeply affected me.
I saw the first of these landscapes, about 10 years ago, off the wild and steep coasts of South Africa.
Every summer, huge banks of sardines move north, a mass migration phenomenon called the Sardine Run.
A crazy race of these fish
where hordes of hungry and agile predators chase them.
Common dolphins hunt together and manage to isolate sardines from the main bench and create small benches.
They dive and trap the fish up, against the surface and rush to appreciate their wriggling feast.
Sharks follow closely.
For many people, sharks and dolphins are sworn enemies, but during the Sardine Run, they live together.
In fact, dolphins help sharks feed more effectively.
Without dolphins, the small benches created are more sparse and sharks often end up with a "sardine doughnut" or a bite of water.
I had a few animated moments with the sharks on the Sardine Run, but I know they don't see me as a prey.
I get shots and am jostled like all the other participants of this banquet fighter.
Let's leave the African coasts, to go east, through the immensity of the Indian Ocean to the Maldives, an archipelago of coral islands.
During the monsoon season, the manta rays of the entire archipelago travel to a tiny islet of Baa Atoll called Hanifaru.
Crustacean armies, most smaller than a marble, are the staple food of the manta rays.
When plankton concentrations are low, the manta rays feed on themselves and they make back, looped pirouettes like a puppy chasing his tail.
When the plankton density increases, the lines line up at the tail and form these long chains. Each delicious bite that escapes the first is swallowed by the second or the next.
When the concentration of plankton reaches its peak, the manta rays swim ever closer in a rotating movement by which they feed.
As they swirl in this narrow formation, the manta line column creates its own vortex, sucking and bringing the right plankton into the cavernous mouth of the rays.
The experience of diving among these countless rays is absolutely unforgettable.
The first time I photographed Hanifaru, the site was unprotected and threatened by development.
I worked with NGOs like Manta Trust, and my photos helped make Hanifaru a marine protected area.
Fishermen from the nearby islands hunted these manta rays, they used their skin to make traditional drums.
Today, they are the most fervent conservatives and the manta rays bring to the maldive economy more than 8 million dollars each year.
I always wanted to go back in time and see an era where the cards were incomplete or indicated: "Here dragons".
I approached the most by visiting these remote atolls in the heart of the Indian Ocean.
Far, far away, from the lines of the boats and fishing, diving into these waters is a poignant memory of what our oceans once looked alike.
Bassas da India is greatly unknown. It is a tiny corner of coral in the Mozambique Channel.
His barrier forms a shield that protects his inner lagoon, a nursery for the Galapagos sharks.
These sharks are anything but shy, even during the day.
Something told me they would be even more bold and more numerous at night.
I found myself facing more sharks than ever, gathered on a simple outcry.
Photographing and sharing moments like these reminds me why I chose this path.
A short time ago, I was working on a project in Lower California for National Geographic.
Halfway, going down the Pacific coast, is San Ignacio Lagoon, where the grey whale comes to give birth.
For a century, this coast was the scene of a systematic massacre, more than 20 000 gray whales were killed, leaving only a few hundred.
Today, the descendants of these same whales play on the surface with their offspring and they even interact with us.
This species has been remarkably derived.
On the other side of the peninsula is Cabo Pulmo, a sleepy fishing village.
Decades of overfishing have taken them to the gates of collapse.
In 1995, local fishermen convinced the authorities to make their waters a marine reserve.
But what happened next is a miracle.
In 2005, after only a decade of protection, scientists recorded the largest increase in fish.
But don't take my word for it, come with me.
In a breath, swim deep with me in the middle of one of the largest and densest schools of fish I have ever encountered.
We all have the opportunity to raise hope.
And through my photos, I would like to convey the message that it is not too late for our oceans.
And I would particularly like to highlight the resistance of nature to 7.3 billion people.
My hope is that in the future, I must search hard to take photos like this, while creating images that show our respectful coexistence with the ocean that,
I hope, will become the everyday for me.
To thrive and survive doing my job, you really have to be an unwavering optimist.
I always work thinking that the next fabulous image that will serve my purpose is ready, just behind the next reef, in the heart of the next lagoon, or who knows, maybe in the next one.
When I moved to Harare in 1985, social justice was at the heart of Zimbabwe's national health policy.
The new government was emerging from a long war of independence and immediately announced a socialist program: health services, primary education became essentially free.
A significant expansion of rural health centres has placed about 80% of the population within two hours of walking of one of these centres, a truly remarkable achievement.
In 1980, the year of independence, 25% of Zimbabwe's children were completely immunized.
In 1990, a decade later, this proportion was 80%.
I felt extremely privileged to be part of this transformation, a revolution.
The excitement, the camaraderie was palpable.
Working with brilliant Zimbabweans — scientists, doctors, activists — I felt connected not only to an African independence movement, but to a progressive global movement for public health.
But there were considerable challenges.
Zimbabwe reported its first AIDS case in 1985, the year I arrived.
I had taken care of a few AIDS patients in the early 80’s, during my medical training at Harlem Hospital, but — we had no idea what was waiting for Africa.
My first few days there, the infection rate was 2%.
It was going to skyrocket and reach one in four adults by my departure from Harare, 17 years later.
In the mid-90's, I had told hundreds of people in the strength of the age that they had HIV.
I had seen friends and colleagues, my students, die in the hospital.
In response to that, my colleagues and I set up a clinic.
We were demonstrating the use of condoms.
We started school education, interventions in the workplace.
We were doing research. We were advising partners of infected men to protect themselves.
We worked hard, and back then I thought I was doing my best.
I provided excellent treatment, as good as possible.
But I was not talking about structural change.
Former UN Secretary Kofi Annan spoke honestly about his personal failure leading to the Rwandan genocide.
In 1994, he was the director of the UN Peace Department.
At a memorial 10 years later, he said: “At the time, I thought I was doing my best, but I realized after the genocide that I could and should have done more to sound the alarm and gather support. »
The AIDS epidemic took the health community by surprise, and today, when the World Health Organization estimates that 39 million people have died from this disease, I am not alone in having remorse and regret for not having done more, sooner.
But when I lived in Zimbabwe, I didn't see my role as a defender or a politician.
I was there because of my technical skills, my clinical skills and my epidemiological research.
For me, my job was to take care of patients and do research to better understand the patterns of transmission within the population, and I was hoping that we would slow down the spread of the virus.
I was aware that marginalized populations had a very high risk of having and dying from AIDS.
And in sugar plantations, which, up close, looked more like feudal strongholds than any modern company, 60% of pregnant women had HIV.
I worked to show that being infected was not a moral failure but rather a culture of male superiority, forced immigrant labour and colonialism.
The whites were largely spared.
As health professionals, our tools were pitifully weak: begging people to change their individual behavior, use condoms, reduce the number of partners.
Infection rates were rising. And when treatment was available in the West, treatment that remained our most powerful weapon against the virus, it was not affordable for the African public sector.
I have not denounced the unequal access to these life-saving drugs or the underlying economic and political systems that raised infection rates in large groups of the population.
I rationalized my silence by telling myself that I was only a visitor in this country, that sounding the alarm could make me expel, prevent me from doing my job, taking care of my patients, doing much necessary research.
So I did not revolt against the government’s initial position on AIDS.
I did not express my concerns out loud.
Many doctors and health professionals may think that I have done nothing wrong.
Our pact with our patients, the Hippocrates oath and its variants, evokes the inviolability of the patient-doctor relationship.
I did everything I could for every patient I had.
But I knew that epidemics appear along the cracks in our society, reflecting not only our biology, but more notably patterns of marginalization, exclusion, discrimination related to race, gender, sexuality, class, etc.
That was true for AIDS.
This was true recently for Ebola.
Medical anthropologists like Paul Farmer, who worked on AIDS in Haiti, called it “structural violence.” Structural because inequalities are embedded in the political and economic organization of our social world, and are often invisible to the eyes of privileged people and to power; and violence because its impact — premature deaths, suffering, disease — is violent.
We do little for our patients if we do not recognize these social injustices.
Sounding the alarm is the first step towards good public health practice, and that is how we could gather back support to revolutionize and create change together.
Today, I do not remain silent.
I’m talking about a lot of things, even if they make those who listen to them uncomfortable, even if they make me uncomfortable.
Much of what I say is related to racial differences and institutionalized racism, things that are no longer supposed to exist in this country, much less in medical practice or public health.
But they exist and we pay them by shortening lives.
That is why sounding the alarm about the impact of racism on health in the United States, the current institutional and interpersonal violence facing people of color, embraced with our sad legacy of 250 years of slavery, 90 years of Jim Crow and 60 years of imperfect equality, sounding the alarm about it is fundamental to the successful completion of my work as a New York City Health Commissioner.
In New York, premature mortality — or dying before it is 65 — is 50 percent higher for black men than for whites.
In 2012, a black woman was 10 times more likely than a white woman to die while giving birth.
Although we have made huge strides to reduce infant mortality rates, a black baby is still nearly three times more likely than a white baby to die in his first year.
New York is no exception.
These statistics are paralleled with statistics made across the United States.
A recent analysis by the New York Times reported that there was, in the country,
1.5 million black men missing. They mentioned the fact that more than one in six black men who are now between 25 and 54 years old no longer lead a normal life, but were in prison or died prematurely.
There is a great injustice in the face of the daily and disproportionate violence against young black men, on which the attention of the recent protests of #BlackLivesMatter is focused.
But we must remember that persistently disparate rates and the occurrence and outcome of common diseases — heart disease, cancer, diabetes, HIV — diseases that can kill gently and silently and take even more black lives prematurely.
When the #BlackLivesMatter movement took shape, I was frustrated and angry that the medical community was reluctant to use the word “racism” in our research and work.
You must have felt something every time I said it.
Our students have participated in white-blouse demonstrations, but the majority of the medical community has stood aside while current discrimination continues to affect the pattern of disease and mortality.
And I am afraid that the fashion of a personalized and precise medicine, the search for biological or genetic targets for a more suitable treatment, could, inadvertently, make us lose sight of the global situation, that is to say the daily context, where a person lives, grows, works, likes, fundamental factor in the determination of the health of the population: for too many of us, poor health.
As health professionals, in our daily work, whether in practice or in research, we are witnessing a great injustice: the homeless who are unable to follow medical advice because they have other priorities; transgender youth who think of suicide because our society is too rigid; the single mother who is made to feel responsible for the poor state of health of her child.
Our role as healthcare professionals is not only to treat our patients but to sound the alarm and promote change.
Whether it is by right or not, our position in society makes us very credible and we should not spoil that.
I regret not having spoken in Zimbabwe, and I have promised myself that, as the Health Commissioner of New York City, I will use every opportunity to sound the alarm and get support for health equity.
I will denounce racism, and I hope that you will join me, and I will join you in denouncing sexism or any other form of inequality.
It is time to stand up and, as a community, to denounce structural inequalities.
We don't need to have all the answers to call for change.
We only need courage.
The health of our patients, of all of us, depends on it.
By hand: how many of you have already deleted a Facebook friend because he had made an offensive remark about politics, religion, parenting, food?
How many of you avoid at least one person just so you don't have to talk to him?
Before, to have a polite conversation, we followed advice from Henry Higgins in "My Fair Lady": stick to the weather and your health.
But nowadays, with climate change and the anti-vaccination movement, these subjects... are no longer very safe.
The world in which we live, this world where any conversation can potentially evolve into controversy, where our politicians cannot talk to each other, and where even the most futile subjects have supporters and critics, this world is not normal.
Pew Research has done a study of 10 000 American adults and has found that, currently, we are more polarized, more divided, than ever before.
We make less compromise, which means we don’t listen to each other.
We decide where to live, who to marry and even who will be our friends, according to our already established convictions.
Again, that doesn’t mean we’re not listening.
A conversation requires a balance between talking and listening, and, somewhere on the way, we have lost that balance.
This is partly because of the technology.
The cell phones you all have, either in your hands or close enough to be able to catch them quickly.
According to Pew Research, about a third of American teens send more than 100 text messages a day.
Many of them, the majority in fact, are likely to text their friends rather than talk to them face to face.
