No doubt you don’t know Kenema in Sierra Leone, or Arua in Nigeria.
For me these are the two most extraordinary places on Earth.
There, in hospitals, there is a community of nurses, doctors and scientists who have calmly fought one of the deadliest threats of humanity in years: the Lassa virus.
The Lassa virus is like the Ebola virus.
It can cause a high fever and can often be fatal.
But these people risk their lives every day, to protect individuals in their communities, and ultimately protect us all.
One of the most extraordinary things I learned about them, during one of my first visits, a long time ago, was that they started every morning - these difficult mornings on the front lines - singing.
They gather together, and they show their joy and strength.
Over the years, we have visited each other. I could be among them, sing, and write. It was extraordinary, because it reminds us that we are not only there for science, but that we are bound by a shared humanity.
You can imagine it, it's extremely important, vital even, when things started to change.
The situation changed in March 2014, when the Ebola outbreak was declared in Guinea.
It was the first outbreak in West Africa, near the border of Sierra Leone and Liberia.
It was scary... We were all terrified.
We had been suspecting for some time that Lassa and Ebola viruses were more widespread than previously thought, that it could reach Kenema.
So, members of my team immediately joined Dr. Humarr Khan and his team on the field. We have implemented diagnostics to carry out molecular tests capable of detecting the arrival of Ebola in Sierra Leone.
We had already managed to control the Lassa virus. We knew how to do it, the team was remarkable.
We just had to give them the tools and the Ebola lab.
Unfortunately, that day has arrived.
On May 23, 2014, a woman arrived in the maternity service of the hospital. The team conducted the molecular tests and identified the first case of Ebola in Sierra Leone.
It was an exceptional job.
They were able to diagnose the case immediately, treat the patient safely, and begin to understand what was going on.
It could have prevented what happened.
But the day it happened, the epidemic had been brewing for several months.
There were already hundreds of cases, surpassing all previous outbreaks.
She entered Sierra Leone, not like this singular case, but as a tidal wave.
We have worked with the international community, the Ministry of Health, with Kenema, to deal with the cases. The following week there were 31, then 92, then 147 cases, they all came to Kenema, one of the only places in Sierra Leone that could solve this problem.
We worked tirelessly, trying everything possible to help each person, and trying to get attention. We also did something else:
We did not throw away the blood tests, used to detect Ebola, we put them in a chemical to deactivate them. We packed and shipped them across the ocean.
We sent them to Boston, where my team works.
We also worked tirelessly, day after day. We quickly generated 99 genomes of the Ebola virus.
The genome is the architect of a virus.
We all have one.
It indicates what we are made of, and transmits so much information about us.
The results of this kind of work are simple and very useful.
We took these 99 different viruses, we observed and compared them, and we found that, by comparing them to the three genomes that had previously been published in Guinea, the epidemic had emerged in Guinea several months earlier, and that, once in humans, it was transmitted from human to human.
This is very important when you want to determine how to intervene, because contact screening is essential.
It has also been discovered that the virus mutates by moving between humans.
Every mutation is important because diagnoses, vaccines, and our therapies are all based on the genome sequence. That's the guide.
Global health experts need to respond, develop and re-calibrate all their work accordingly.
But science doesn’t work that way. My position at the time was that I had the data and I could have worked in silo for months, analyze the data carefully, slowly, submit an article for publication, make some changes, and finally publish my data after the official publication.
This is how the status quo in science works.
This time, there is no question of doing so.
We had friends on the ground. For us, it was obvious that we needed help, a lot of help...
The first thing we did, as soon as the machine released the first sequences, was to publish them on the web.
We published them and issued a call for help.
And the help came!
Quickly, many people contacted us, surprised by the data we had published.
Some of the world’s greatest infectiologists were part of our community.
We worked together virtually, sharing regular calls, trying to track the virus minute by minute, to see how to stop it.
There are so many ways to form such communities.
Everyone, when the epidemic began to spread globally, wanted to learn, participate, and engage.
Everyone wanted to play a role.
The number of volunteers was incredible, and the Internet connected us all.
Can you imagine that instead of being afraid of each other, we would say, “OK, let’s go, working together,
We will defeat this virus. »
The problem was that the data we used, while researching the web, was too limited for our purpose.
We're wasting a lot of opportunities in these cases.
So when the outbreak broke out in Kenema, we had 106 patient clinical records, and we made them public.
In our lab, we have shown that, with these 106 files, we can teach our computers to predict Ebola with an accuracy of about 100%.
We have developed an app that gives access to this information to on-site healthcare workers.
Unfortunately, 106 cases are not sufficient to consolidate and validate the data.
So we expected more data.
But we were still waiting for the data.
We are still waiting, confined to our silos, instead of working together.
This situation is no longer tolerable.
You, all of you, can't accept that anymore.
It's our life that's at stake.
Many people lost their lives, health workers, including colleagues who were dear to me. Five colleagues lost their lives: Mbalu Fonnie, Alex Moigboi, Dr. Humarr Khan, Alice Koroma and Mohamed Fullah.
These are just five of many among many in Kenema and beyond, dead, while the world was waiting and we were working, quietly and separately.
Ebola, like all threats to humanity, is fueled by mistrust, confusion and division.
While we are building barriers between us, the virus develops.
Unlike all other threats, in front of Ebola, we are all equal.
We are all on the same boat.
Ebola is on our threshold to all.
And so in this place, we share the same vulnerabilities, strengths, fears and hopes, I hope that we can work together and with pleasure.
One of my former students was reading a book about Sierra Leone, and she discovered that the term “Kenema,” the hospital where we work in Sierra Leone, comes from Mende’s quote for “clear as a river, translucent and open to eyes.”
It had a special meaning for us, because, without knowing it, we had always thought that to honor individuals in Kenema, we had to work openly and together.
We have to do it.
We must all demand of ourselves and others, to be open to the other, when an epidemic occurs, and to fight it together.
Because this is neither the first Ebola outbreak, nor the last, and there are many other pathogens around us, like the Lassa virus.
The next outbreak could affect a city of millions of people.
It could start there and be transmitted by air.
It could even be deliberately scattered.
I know it's scary, I understand... but I also know, this experience proves to us, that we have the technology and the ability to win, to win and get ahead of other viruses.
But it is only possible if we collaborate in joy.
For Dr. Khan, and for all those who gave their lives, on the front, in this fight with us, let us be by their side in this struggle. Always.
Let us not leave the world with the stigma of the destruction caused by a virus. Let us illuminate it with the brightness of billions of hearts and minds working in unity.
Thank you.
